+ Brief von Major Minchin an J Hodges __________________________2 Aug 1854.

My dear brother!
.an 2
----------
1. ... in der Abschrift.

.fo +
I will gladly do whatever you wish ...611 I do not consider Mr. Metz the Sen-
ior Miss[ionar]y and from the wording of the will I consider the Testator
intended there should be always at least 2 Missionaries: and as I feel my
duty is to see the wishes of the Testator carried out. I am determined to
do so. - Mr Moericke I look upon as the Senior Miss[ionar]y. His removal
was never officially reported to me and I consider an attempt has been made
by the Home Committee to throw overboard all the wishes and feelings of the
Trustees appointed by the Testator. Mr Casamajor expressed a wish to me
that Mr Moericke should be one of the Miss[ionar]y on the hills, and I con-
sider him the Trustee in Mr Bhlers place.

So strongly do I feel the injustice and breach of faith on the part of the
Home Comm. that if Mr Moericke is not sent back I will only consent to pay
half the money realized to Mr Metz and will keep the other half in Arbuth-
not's hands.

As executor I will also retain the œ 2300 which I hope soon to receive from
Mess. Harkly and Co., and will not give it over to the Trustees till Mr
Moericke is sent back. And if the Trustees like to try the point I am sat-
isfied, the Court of Chancery will support me in defending my Trust, and as
I am sole Executor I am alone responsible that the wishes of the Testator
are fully carried out. ...611
.an 2
----------
1. ... in der Abschrift.

You can show this letter to Dr Gundert if you like, as I am still almost
confined to my chair and shall not now see him
.fo -
                        Yours affect Fred Minchin.




+ Aus den letzten Tagen von Bruder M. Bhler. ________________________1854.

